2026-06-24 00:00:15,018 INFO msg #135: assistant (4723 chars)
I now have enough grounding in the actual contracts (`crosswalk.py`, `config.py`, `elo.py`'s `_SORT_COLS`/`MatchEloDiff`, `poisson.py`'s `decay_weight`/`TeamAbilities`, `martj42_loader.wc2026_schedule`, and `live.py`'s `TournamentState`) to evaluate the cycle. Key findings: dependency chain #7→#8→#9→#10 is linear and non-circular; agent assignment (`python-pro`) fits; files are disjoint. Three concrete, actionable issues surfaced — the sort-key duplication that the whole alignment contract rests on (#8), the O(N²) per-row prefix scans in the assembler (#9), and the missing key to filter WC2026 rows from the built frame (#10).

```json
{
  "decisions": [
    { "issue_number": 7, "action": "ok", "comment_body": "" },
    { "issue_number": 8, "action": "comment", "comment_body": "The alignment contract this cycle depends on — the chronologically sorted frame being positionally 1:1 with EloResult.match_diffs — hinges on sort_chronological reproducing the Elo engine's sort byte-for-byte. But the plan has you declare a *new* sort-key constant in timeaware.py rather than reuse the engine's. Two independent literals will silently drift if elo.py's sort key ever changes, and the only symptom is leaked/misaligned features downstream. Fix: promote elo.py's private _SORT_COLS to a public name (e.g. elo.SORT_COLS) and import it here instead of re-declaring the list; replicate the full transform exactly — assign _d=pd.to_datetime(df['DATE'], errors='coerce'), sort_values(SORT_COLS, kind='stable', na_position='last'), drop _d, reset_index(drop=True). Add a test that runs a constructed frame through both the engine's ordering and sort_chronological and asserts row-for-row equality, so any future divergence fails loudly here rather than only in #9's runtime alignment guard. Separately, make the reference date for recent_form's decay explicit: anchor age_days to the *current* match date (D − prior_match_date) so 'time-weighted' is unambiguous and testable." },
    { "issue_number": 9, "action": "comment", "comment_body": "Performance-as-correctness risk in the per-row composition. As specified, recent_form, goal_difference, and rest_days each scan the prefix rows[:before_idx] for the team, and build() invokes them for both teams on every match. Over the full martj42 history (~tens of thousands of internationals) that is O(N²) prefix scans — a single build can run for many minutes and will dominate Cycle-5 backtests that rebuild repeatedly, with no runtime bound in the acceptance criteria to catch it. Root cause: re-deriving each team's prior matches from scratch on every row. Fix: make one chronological pass that maintains per-team incremental state (a rolling deque of recent played results + running goal-diff + last-played date), or build a per-team appearance index dict[team] -> list[(idx, date, points, goal_diff)] once and have the helpers take a windowed slice (O(window)) instead of an O(before_idx) scan. Keep the pure leaf helpers for the #8 leakage unit tests, but route build() through the indexed path so there is one tested code path rather than a fast production path diverging from the tested-but-slow helpers. Minor: MatchFeatures labels are typed int | None while inputs are nullable Int64 — convert pd.NA to None explicitly so the dataclass round-trips (the frame can keep <NA>)." },
    { "issue_number": 10, "action": "comment", "comment_body": "The plan is right to build over the full chronologically-sorted history and then filter to WC2026 rows — that preserves correct before_idx (no-leakage) semantics, and the explicit 'do NOT run the builder on the WC2026 subset alone' guard is the correct call. But there is a concrete gap: the assembler's MatchFeatures / output frame exposes no tournament, stage, or match-id column, so there is no key to select the WC2026 rows after building. Do not re-derive the subset by joining on (date, home, away) — neutral-site duplicates and same-day fixtures can collide and silently mis-select. Fix: compute the mask positionally — sort_chronological(df)['TOURNAMENT'] == 'FIFA World Cup' is row-for-row aligned with the output frame, so apply that boolean mask by position; alternatively coordinate with the assembler to pass through a non-covariate 'tournament' identifier column (metadata, not a feature, so it stays inside the football-only allow-list). Add a test asserting a WC2026 fixture's row carries pre-match form/rest/Elo that reflects the team's non-WC prior matches, proving the full-history build (not a WC-only build) produced it. The no-key martj42 path and the key-gated live path matching the verified TournamentState(played, remaining_group_fixtures, standings) shape are otherwise well-specified." }
